Bad (stateful singleton) vs Good (stateless singleton):
// BAD ❌
// Shared instance field gets overwritten by threads

@Service
public class PaymentService {

    private String currentUser;

    public void pay(String user) {

        currentUser = user;

        // imagine some delay here

        System.out.println(currentUser + " paid");
    }
}
Problem:
Thread 1 → pay("Kams")
Thread 2 → pay("John")

currentUser gets overwritten 
Output may become:
John paid
John paid
even though Kams also paid.
Now the correct version:
// GOOD ✅
// No shared user-specific state

@Service
public class PaymentService {

    public void pay(String user) {

        // local variable (thread-safe)
        String currentUser = user;

        System.out.println(currentUser + " paid");
    }
}
Why safe?
Thread 1 → own stack → "Kams"
Thread 2 → own stack → "John"
No overwriting happens because local variables belong to each thread separately.
Golden rule:
Singleton + instance fields holding user data = dangerous

Singleton + method parameters/local variables = safe
